# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: orbital-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Although the term *escape velocity* is common, it is more accurately described as a speed than as a velocity because it is independent of direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Because gravitational force between two objects depends on their combined mass, the escape speed also depends on mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For artificial satellites and small natural objects, the mass of the object makes a negligible contribution to the combined mass, and so is often ignored.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Escape speed varies with distance from the center of the primary body, as does the velocity of an object traveling under the gravitational influence of the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] If an object is in a circular or elliptical orbit, its speed is always less than the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] In contrast if it is on a hyperbolic trajectory its speed will always be higher than the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] (It will slow down as it gets to greater distance, but does so asymptotically approaching a positive speed.) An object on a parabolic trajectory will always be traveling exactly the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] It has precisely balanced positive kinetic energy and negative gravitational potential energy; it will always be slowing down, asymptotically approaching zero speed, but never quite stop.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Escape velocity calculations are typically used to determine whether an object will remain in the gravitational sphere of influence of a given body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For example, in solar system exploration it is useful to know whether a probe will continue to orbit the Earth or escape to a heliocentric orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] It is also useful to know how much a probe will need to slow down in order to be gravitationally captured by its destination body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Rockets do not have to reach escape velocity in a single maneuver, and objects can also use a gravity assist to siphon kinetic energy away from large bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Precise trajectory calculations require taking into account small forces like atmospheric drag, radiation pressure, and solar wind.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] A rocket under continuous or intermittent thrust (or an object climbing a space elevator) can attain escape at any non-zero speed, but the minimum amount of energy required to do so is always the same.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The value *GM* is called the standard gravitational parameter, or *μ*, and is often known more accurately than either *G* or *M* separately.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] A related quantity is the specific orbital energy which is essentially the sum of the kinetic and potential energy divided by the mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] An object has reached escape velocity when the specific orbital energy is greater than or equal to zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The existence of escape velocity can be thought of as a consequence of conservation of energy and an energy field of finite depth.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Adding speed (kinetic energy) to an object expands the region of locations it can reach, until, with enough energy, everywhere to infinity becomes accessible.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The formula for escape velocity can be derived from the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For the sake of simplicity, unless stated otherwise, we assume that an object will escape the gravitational field of a uniform spherical planet by moving away from it and that the only significant force acting on the moving object is the planet's gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Imagine that a spaceship of mass *m* is initially at a distance *r* from the center of mass of the planet, whose mass is *M*, and its initial speed is equal to its escape velocity, *v*e.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] At its final state, it will be an infinite distance away from the planet, and its speed will be negligibly small.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The same result is obtained by a relativistic calculation, in which case the variable *r* represents the *radial coordinate* or *reduced circumference* of the Schwarzschild metric.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] where *r* is the distance between the center of the body and the point at which escape velocity is being calculated and *g* is the gravitational acceleration at that distance (i.e., the surface gravity).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For a body with a spherically symmetric distribution of mass, the escape velocity *v*e from the surface is proportional to the radius assuming constant density, and proportional to the square root of the average density *ρ*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] This escape velocity is relative to a non-rotating frame of reference, not relative to the moving surface of the planet or moon, as explained below.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The escape velocity *relative to the surface* of a rotating body depends on direction in which the escaping body travels.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The surface velocity decreases with the cosine of the geographic latitude, so space launch facilities are often located as close to the equator as feasible, e.g. the American Cape Canaveral (latitude 28°28′ N) and the French Guiana Space Centre (latitude 5°14′ N).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For an actual escape orbit, a spacecraft will accelerate steadily out of the atmosphere until it reaches the escape velocity appropriate for its altitude (which will be less than on the surface).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] In many cases, the spacecraft may be first placed in a parking orbit (e.g. a low Earth orbit at 160–2,000 km) and then accelerated to the escape velocity at that altitude, which will be slightly lower (about 11.0 km/s at a low Earth orbit of 200 km).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The required additional change in speed, however, is far less because the spacecraft already has a significant orbital speed (in low Earth orbit speed is approximately 7.8 km/s, or 28,080 km/h).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The escape velocity at a given height is ${\sqrt {2}}$ times the speed in a circular orbit at the same height, (compare this with the velocity equation in circular orbit).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] This corresponds to the fact that the potential energy with respect to infinity of an object in such an orbit is minus two times its kinetic energy, while to escape the sum of potential and kinetic energy needs to be at least zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The velocity corresponding to the circular orbit is sometimes called the **first cosmic velocity**, whereas in this context the escape velocity is referred to as the **second cosmic velocity**.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For a body in an elliptical orbit wishing to accelerate to an escape orbit the required speed will vary, and will be greatest at periapsis when the body is closest to the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] However, the orbital speed of the body will also be at its highest at this point, and the change in velocity required will be at its lowest, as explained by the Oberth effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Escape velocity can either be measured as relative to the other, central body or relative to center of mass or barycenter of the system of bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Thus for systems of two bodies, the term *escape velocity* can be ambiguous, but it is usually intended to mean the barycentric escape velocity of the less massive body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Escape velocity usually refers to the escape velocity of zero mass test particles.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] For zero mass test particles we have that the 'relative to the other' and the 'barycentric' escape velocities are the same, namely $v_{\text{e}}={\sqrt {\frac {2GM}{d}}}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] But when we can't neglect the smaller mass (say *m*) we arrive at slightly different formulas.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Because the system has to obey the law of conservation of momentum we see that both the larger and the smaller mass must be accelerated in the gravitational field.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Relative to the center of mass the velocity of the larger mass (*v*p, for planet) can be expressed in terms of the velocity of the smaller mass (*v*r, for rocket).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] where *x* = *v*/*v*e is the ratio of the original speed *v* to the escape velocity *v*e.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Unlike escape velocity, the direction (vertically up) is important to achieve maximum height.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] If an object attains exactly escape velocity, but is not directed straight away from the planet, then it will follow a curved path or trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Although this trajectory does not form a closed shape, it can be referred to as an orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The shape of the trajectory will be a parabola whose focus is located at the center of mass of the planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] An actual escape requires a course with a trajectory that does not intersect with the planet, or its atmosphere, since this would cause the object to crash.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] When moving away from the source, this path is called an escape orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Escape orbits are known as *C*3 = 0 orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] *C*3 is the characteristic energy, −*GM*/2*a*, where *a* is the semi-major axis length, which is infinite for parabolic trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] If the body has a velocity greater than escape velocity then its path will form a hyperbolic trajectory and it will have an excess hyperbolic velocity, equivalent to the extra energy the body has.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] A relatively small extra delta-*v* above that needed to accelerate to the escape speed can result in a relatively large speed at infinity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Some orbital manoeuvres make use of this fact.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] If a body in circular orbit (or at the periapsis of an elliptical orbit) accelerates along its direction of travel to escape velocity, the point of acceleration will form the periapsis of the escape trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The eventual direction of travel will be at 90 degrees to the direction at the point of acceleration.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] If the body accelerates to beyond escape velocity the eventual direction of travel will be at a smaller angle, and indicated by one of the asymptotes of the hyperbolic trajectory it is now taking.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] This means the timing of the acceleration is critical if the intention is to escape in a particular direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] This is valid for elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] In this table, the left-hand half gives the escape velocity from the visible surface of the planet or moon (which may be gaseous, for example Jupiter) relative to its centre (that is, not relative to its moving surface).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] In the right-hand half, *V*e refers to the speed relative to the central body (for example the sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] The values in the last column are variable, depending on precisely where in a body’s orbit escape velocity is reached, as the orbits are elliptical, not circular (particularly those of Mercury and Pluto).
[src:orbital-mechanics/escape-velocity] Let *G* be the gravitational constant and let *M* be the mass of the earth (or other gravitating body) and *m* be the mass of the escaping body or projectile.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Gravity assistance can be used to accelerate a spacecraft, that is, to increase or decrease its speed or redirect its path.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The "assist" is provided by the motion of the gravitating body as it pulls on the spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Any gain or loss of kinetic energy and linear momentum by a passing spacecraft is correspondingly lost or gained by the gravitational body, in accordance with Newton's Third Law.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The gravity assist maneuver was first used in 1959 when the Soviet probe Luna 3 photographed the far side of Earth's Moon, and it was used by interplanetary probes from Mariner 10 onward, including the two Voyager probes' notable flybys of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A gravity assist around a planet changes a spacecraft's velocity (relative to the Sun) by entering and leaving the gravitational sphere of influence of a planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The sum of the kinetic energies of both bodies remains constant (see elastic collision).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A slingshot maneuver can therefore be used to change the spaceship's trajectory and speed relative to the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A close terrestrial analogy is provided by a tennis ball bouncing off the front of a moving train.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Imagine standing on a train platform, and throwing a ball at 30 km/h toward a train approaching at 50 km/h.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The driver of the train sees the ball approaching at 80 km/h and then departing at 80 km/h after the ball bounces elastically off the front of the train.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Because of the train's motion, however, that departure is at 130 km/h relative to the train platform; the ball has added twice the train's velocity to its own.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Translating this analogy into space: in the planet reference frame, the spaceship has a vertical velocity of *v* relative to the planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] After the slingshot occurs the spaceship is leaving on a course 90 degrees to that which it arrived on.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] It will still have a velocity of *v*, but in the horizontal direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In the Sun reference frame, the planet has a horizontal velocity of v, and by using the Pythagorean Theorem, the spaceship initially has a total velocity of √2*v*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] After the spaceship leaves the planet, it will have a velocity of *v + v =* 2*v*, gaining approximately 0.6*v*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] This oversimplified example cannot be refined without additional details regarding the orbit, but if the spaceship travels in a path which forms a hyperbola, it can leave the planet in the opposite direction without firing its engine.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] This example is one of many trajectories and gains of speed the spaceship can experience.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] This explanation might seem to violate the conservation of energy and momentum, apparently adding velocity to the spacecraft out of nothing, but the spacecraft's effects on the planet must also be taken into consideration to provide a complete picture of the mechanics involved.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The linear momentum gained by the spaceship is equal in magnitude to that lost by the planet, so the spacecraft gains velocity and the planet loses velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] However, the planet's enormous mass compared to the spacecraft makes the resulting change in its speed negligibly small even when compared to the orbital perturbations planets undergo due to interactions with other celestial bodies on astronomically short timescales.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] For example, one metric ton is a typical mass for an interplanetary space probe whereas Jupiter has a mass of almost 2 × 1024 metric tons.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Therefore, a one-ton spacecraft passing Jupiter will theoretically cause the planet to lose approximately 5 × 10−25 km/s of orbital velocity for every km/s of velocity relative to the Sun gained by the spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] For all practical purposes the effects on the planet can be ignored in the calculation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Realistic portrayals of encounters in space require the consideration of three dimensions.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The same principles apply as above except adding the planet's velocity to that of the spacecraft requires vector addition as shown below.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Due to the reversibility of orbits, gravitational slingshots can also be used to reduce the speed of a spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Both Mariner 10 and MESSENGER performed this maneuver to reach Mercury.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] If more speed is needed than available from gravity assist alone, a rocket burn near the periapsis (closest planetary approach) uses the least fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A given rocket burn always provides the same change in velocity (Δv), but the change in kinetic energy is proportional to the vehicle's velocity at the time of the burn.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Therefore the maximum kinetic energy is obtained when the burn occurs at the vehicle's maximum velocity (periapsis).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The Oberth effect describes this technique in more detail.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The portion of his manuscript considering gravity-assists received no later development and was not published until the 1960s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Italian engineer Gaetano Crocco was first to calculate an interplanetary journey considering multiple gravity-assists in 1956.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The gravity assist maneuver was first used in 1959 when the Soviet probe Luna 3 photographed the far side of the Moon.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The maneuver relied on research performed under the direction of Mstislav Keldysh at the Keldysh Institute of Applied Mathematics.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In 1961, Michael Minovitch, UCLA graduate student who worked at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL), developed a gravity assist technique, that would later be used for the Gary Flandro's Planetary Grand Tour idea.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] During the summer of 1964 at the NASA JPL, Gary Flandro was assigned the task of studying techniques for exploring the outer planets of the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In this study he discovered the rare alignment of the outer planets (Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune) and conceived the Planetary Grand Tour multi-planet mission utilizing gravity assist to reduce mission duration from forty years to less than ten.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A spacecraft traveling from Earth to an inner planet will increase its relative speed because it is falling toward the Sun, and a spacecraft traveling from Earth to an outer planet will decrease its speed because it is leaving the vicinity of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Rocket engines can certainly be used to increase and decrease the speed of the spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] This is because not only must the primary-stage engines lift the extra propellant, they must also lift the extra propellant beyond that which is needed to lift *that* additional propellant.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The liftoff mass requirement increases exponentially with an increase in the required delta-*v* of the spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Because additional fuel is needed to lift fuel into space, space missions are designed with a tight propellant "budget", known as the "delta-v budget".
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The delta-v budget is in effect the total propellant that will be available after leaving the earth, for speeding up, slowing down, stabilization against external buffeting (by particles or other external effects), or direction changes, if it cannot acquire more propellant.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The entire mission must be planned within that capability.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Therefore, methods of speed and direction change that do not require fuel to be burned are advantageous, because they allow extra maneuvering capability and course enhancement, without spending fuel from the limited amount which has been carried into space.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Gravity assist maneuvers can greatly change the speed of a spacecraft without expending propellant, and can save significant amounts of propellant, so they are a useful technique to save fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The main practical limit to the use of a gravity assist maneuver is that planets and other large masses are seldom in the right places to enable a voyage to a particular destination.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] For example, the Voyager missions which started in the late 1970s were made possible by the "Grand Tour" alignment of Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A similar alignment will not occur again until the middle of the 22nd century.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] That is an extreme case, but even for less ambitious missions there are years when the planets are scattered in unsuitable parts of their orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Another limitation is the distance of closest approach to the planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The magnitude of the change in velocity depends on the spacecraft's approach velocity and the planet's escape velocity at the point of closest approach.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The closer to the center of the planet that approach is, the greater the achievable change in velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The atmosphere, if any, of the available planet will set a limit to the approach distance; for bodies with no atmosphere, like the moon, the closest approach is set by the constraint that the trajectory must not intersect the surface.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] For planets with atmosphere, as a spacecraft gets deep into the atmosphere, the energy lost to drag can exceed that gained from the planet's velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] (On the other hand, this drag can be used to accomplish a different delta-V maneuver, aerobraking).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] There have also been theoretical proposals to use aerodynamic lift as the spacecraft flies through the atmosphere.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] This maneuver, called an aerogravity assist, could bend the trajectory through a larger angle than gravity alone, and hence increase the gain in energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Interplanetary slingshots using the Sun itself are not possible because the Sun is at rest relative to the Solar System as a whole.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] However, thrusting when near the Sun has a related effect, the Oberth effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] This has the potential to magnify a spacecraft's thrusting power enormously, but is limited by the spacecraft's ability to resist the heat.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] For planetary gravity assists, a thrust applied near the closest approach (a "powered periapsis maneuver") can add the Oberth effect to the gravity slingshot effect, producing a larger change in orbital velocity than either effect by itself.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A rotating black hole might provide additional assistance, if its spin axis is aligned the right way.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] General relativity predicts that a large spinning mass produces frame-dragging—close to the object, space itself is dragged around in the direction of the spin.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Any ordinary rotating object produces this effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Although attempts to measure frame dragging about the Sun have produced no clear evidence, experiments performed by Gravity Probe B have detected frame-dragging effects caused by Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] General relativity predicts that a spinning black hole is surrounded by a region of space, called the ergosphere, within which standing still (with respect to the black hole's spin) is impossible, because space itself is dragged at the speed of light in the same direction as the black hole's spin.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The Penrose process may offer a way to gain energy from the ergosphere, although it would require the spaceship to dump some "ballast" into the black hole, and the spaceship would have had to expend energy to carry the "ballast" to the black hole.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The gravity assist maneuver was first attempted in 1959 for Luna 3, to photograph the far side of the Moon.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The satellite did not gain speed, but its orbit was changed in a way that allowed successful transmission of the photos.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] NASA's *Pioneer 10* is a space probe launched in 1972 that completed the first mission to the planet Jupiter.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Thereafter, *Pioneer 10* became the first of five artificial objects to achieve the escape velocity needed to leave the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In December 1973, *Pioneer 10* spacecraft was the first one to use the gravitational slingshot effect to reach escape velocity to leave Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Pioneer 11 was launched by NASA in 1973, to study the asteroid belt, the environment around Jupiter and Saturn, solar winds, and cosmic rays.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] It was the first probe to encounter Saturn, the second to fly through the asteroid belt, and the second to fly by Jupiter (3 December 1974).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] To get to Saturn, the spacecraft got a gravity assist on Jupiter.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The Mariner 10 probe was the first spacecraft to use the gravitational slingshot effect to reach another planet, passing by Venus on 5 February 1974 on its way to becoming the first spacecraft to explore Mercury.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The *Galileo* spacecraft was launched by NASA in 1989 and on its route to Jupiter got three gravity assists, one from Venus (February 10, 1990), and two from Earth (December 8, 1990 and December 8, 1992).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Spacecraft reached Jupiter in December 1995.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Gravity assists also allowed *Galileo* to flyby two asteroids, 243 Ida and 951 Gaspra.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In 1990, NASA launched the ESA spacecraft *Ulysses* to study the polar regions of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] All the planets orbit approximately in a plane aligned with the equator of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Thus, to enter an orbit passing over the poles of the Sun, the spacecraft would have to eliminate the speed it inherited from the Earth's orbit around the Sun and gain the speed needed to orbit the Sun in the pole-to-pole plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] It was achieved by a gravity assist from Jupiter on February 8, 1992.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The MESSENGER mission (launched in August 2004) made extensive use of gravity assists to slow its speed before orbiting Mercury.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The MESSENGER mission included one flyby of Earth, two flybys of Venus, and three flybys of Mercury before finally arriving at Mercury in March 2011 with a velocity low enough to permit orbit insertion with available fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Although the flybys were primarily orbital maneuvers, each provided an opportunity for significant scientific observations.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The *Cassini–Huygens* spacecraft was launched from Earth on 15 October 1997, followed by gravity assist flybys of Venus (26 April 1998 and 21 June 1999), Earth (18 August 1999), and Jupiter (30 December 2000).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Transit to Saturn took 6.7 years, the spacecraft arrived at 1 July 2004.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Its trajectory was called "the Most Complex Gravity-Assist Trajectory Flown to Date" in 2019.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Gravity assists form peaks to the left, while periodic variations on the right are caused by the spacecraft's orbit around Saturn.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] A typical Titan encounter changed the spacecraft's velocity by 0.75 km/s, and the spacecraft made 127 Titan encounters.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] These encounters enabled an orbital tour with a wide range of periapsis and apoapsis distances, various alignments of the orbit with respect to the Sun, and orbital inclinations from 0° to 74°.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The multiple flybys of Titan also allowed Cassini to flyby other moons, such as Rhea and Enceladus.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The *Rosetta* probe, launched in March 2004, used four gravity assist maneuvers (including one just 250 km from the surface of Mars, and three assists from Earth) to accelerate throughout the inner Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] That enabled it to flyby the asteroids 21 Lutetia and 2867 Šteins as well as eventually match the velocity of the 67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko comet at the rendezvous point in August 2014.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The Juno spacecraft was launched on August 5, 2011 (UTC).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The trajectory used a gravity assist speed boost from Earth, accomplished by an Earth flyby in October 2013, two years after its launch on August 5, 2011.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In that way *Juno* changed its orbit (and speed) toward its final goal, Jupiter, after only five years.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The Parker Solar Probe, launched by NASA in 2018, has seven planned Venus gravity assists.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Each gravity assist brings the Parker Solar Probe progressively closer to the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] As of 2022, the spacecraft has performed five of its seven assists.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The Parker Solar Probe's mission will make the closest approach to the Sun by any space mission.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The mission's final planned gravity assist maneuver, completed on November 6, 2024, prepared it for three final solar flybys reaching just 3.8 million miles from the surface of the sun on December 24, 2024 (see figure).
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Solar Orbiter was launched by ESA in 2020.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] In its initial cruise phase, which lasts until November 2021, Solar Orbiter performed two gravity-assist manoeuvres around Venus and one around Earth to alter the spacecraft's trajectory, guiding it towards the innermost regions of the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The first close solar pass took place on 26 March 2022 at around a third of Earth's distance from the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] BepiColombo is a joint mission of the European Space Agency (ESA) and the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) to the planet Mercury.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] It will use the gravity assist technique with Earth once, with Venus twice, and six times with Mercury.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] BepiColombo is named after Giuseppe (Bepi) Colombo who was a pioneer thinker with this way of maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] Europa Clipper, launched by NASA on October 14, 2024, uses gravity assists from Mars and Earth on its way to Jupiter.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] It gained its first gravity assist from Mars on March 1, 2025, and is scheduled to gain its second from Earth during its flyby on December 3, 2026.
[src:orbital-mechanics/gravity-assist] The probe is expected to enter orbit around Jupiter in April 2030, from which it will perform multiple flybys of Europa during the duration of its mission.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In astronautics, the **Hohmann transfer orbit** (/ˈhoʊmən/) is an orbital maneuver used to transfer a spacecraft between two orbits of different altitudes around a central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For example, a Hohmann transfer could be used to raise a satellite's orbit from low Earth orbit to geostationary orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the idealized case, the initial and target orbits are both circular and coplanar.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The maneuver is accomplished by placing the craft into an elliptical transfer orbit that is tangential to both the initial and target orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The maneuver uses two impulsive engine burns: the first establishes the transfer orbit, and the second adjusts the orbit to match the target.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Hohmann maneuver often uses the lowest possible amount of impulse (which consumes a proportional amount of delta-v, and hence propellant) to accomplish the transfer, but requires a relatively longer travel time than higher-impulse transfers.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In some cases where one orbit is much larger than the other, a bi-elliptic transfer can use even less impulse, at the cost of even greater travel time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The maneuver was named after Walter Hohmann, the German scientist who published a description of it in his 1925 book *Die Erreichbarkeit der Himmelskörper* (*The Attainability of Celestial Bodies*).
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Hohmann was influenced in part by the German science fiction author Kurd Lasswitz and his 1897 book *Two Planets*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] When used for traveling between celestial bodies, a Hohmann transfer orbit requires that the starting and destination points be at particular locations in their orbits relative to each other.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Space missions using a Hohmann transfer must wait for this required alignment to occur, which opens a launch window.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For a mission between Earth and Mars, for example, these launch windows occur every 26 months.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] A Hohmann transfer orbit also determines a fixed time required to travel between the starting and destination points; for an Earth-Mars journey this travel time is about 9 months.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] When transfer is performed between orbits close to celestial bodies with significant gravitation, much less delta-v is usually required, as the Oberth effect may be employed for the burns.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] They are also often used for these situations, but low-energy transfers which take into account the thrust limitations of real engines, and take advantage of the gravity wells of both planets can be more fuel efficient.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The diagram shows a Hohmann transfer orbit to bring a spacecraft from a lower circular orbit into a higher one.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] It is an elliptic orbit that is tangential both to the lower circular orbit the spacecraft is to leave (cyan, labeled *1* on diagram) and the higher circular orbit that it is to reach (red, labeled *3* on diagram).
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The transfer orbit (yellow, labeled *2* on diagram) is initiated by firing the spacecraft's engine to add energy and raise the apoapsis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] When the spacecraft reaches the apoapsis, a second engine firing adds energy to raise the periapsis, putting the spacecraft in the larger circular orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The engine is then fired again at the lower distance to slow the spacecraft into the lower circular orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Hohmann transfer orbit is based on two instantaneous velocity changes.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Extra fuel is required to compensate for the fact that the bursts take time; this is minimized by using high-thrust engines to minimize the duration of the bursts.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For transfers in Earth orbit, the two burns are labelled the *perigee burn* and the *apogee burn* (or *apogee kick*); more generally, for bodies that are not the Earth, they are labelled *periapsis* and *apoapsis* burns.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Alternatively, the second burn to circularize the orbit may be referred to as a *circularization burn*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] An ideal Hohmann transfer orbit transfers between two circular orbits in the same plane and traverses exactly 180° around the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the real world, the destination orbit may not be circular, and may not be coplanar with the initial orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Real world transfer orbits may traverse slightly more, or slightly less, than 180° around the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] An orbit which traverses less than 180° around the primary is called a "Type I" Hohmann transfer, while an orbit which traverses more than 180° is called a "Type II" Hohmann transfer.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Transfer orbits can go more than 360° around the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] These multiple-revolution transfers are sometimes referred to as Type III and Type IV, where a Type III is a Type I plus 360°, and a Type IV is a Type II plus 360°.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] A Hohmann transfer orbit can be used to transfer an object's orbit toward another object, as long as they co-orbit a more massive body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the context of Earth and the Solar System, this includes any object which orbits the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] An example of where a Hohmann transfer orbit could be used is to bring an asteroid, orbiting the Sun, into contact with the Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Typically, $\mu$ is given in units of m3/s2; as such one should be sure to use meters, not kilometers, for $r_{1}$ and $r_{2}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In application to traveling from one celestial body to another it is crucial to start maneuver at the time when the two bodies are properly aligned.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Consider a geostationary transfer orbit, beginning at *r*1 = 6,678 km (altitude 300 km) and ending in a geostationary orbit with *r*2 = 42,164 km (altitude 35,786 km).
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the smaller circular orbit the speed is 7.73 km/s; in the larger one, 3.07 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the elliptical orbit in between the speed varies from 10.15 km/s at the perigee to 1.61 km/s at the apogee.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Therefore the Δv for the first burn is 10.15 − 7.73 = 2.42 km/s, for the second burn 3.07 − 1.61 = 1.46 km/s, and for both together 3.88 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This is *greater* than the Δv required for an escape orbit: 10.93 − 7.73 = 3.20 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Applying a Δv at the Low Earth orbit (LEO) of only 0.78 km/s more (3.20−2.42) would give the rocket the escape velocity, which is less than the Δv of 1.46 km/s required to circularize the geosynchronous orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] As the example above demonstrates, the Δ*v* required to perform a Hohmann transfer between two circular orbits is not the greatest when the destination radius is infinite.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] (Escape speed is √2 times orbital speed, so the Δv required to escape is √2 − 1 (41.4%) of the orbital speed.) The Δv required is greatest (53.0% of smaller orbital speed) when the radius of the larger orbit is 15.5817... times that of the smaller orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For higher orbit ratios the Δ*v* required for the second burn decreases faster than the first increases.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For example, consider a spacecraft travelling from Earth to Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] At the beginning of its journey, the spacecraft will already have a certain velocity and kinetic energy associated with its orbit around Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] During the burn the rocket engine applies its delta-*v*, but the kinetic energy increases as a square law, until it is sufficient to escape the planet's gravitational potential, and then burns more so as to gain enough energy to get into the Hohmann transfer orbit (around the Sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Because the rocket engine is able to make use of the initial kinetic energy of the propellant, far less delta-*v* is required over and above that needed to reach escape velocity, and the optimum situation is when the transfer burn is made at minimum altitude (low periapsis) above the planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The delta-*v* needed is only 3.6 km/s, only about 0.4 km/s more than needed to escape Earth, even though this results in the spacecraft going 2.9 km/s faster than the Earth as it heads off for Mars (see table below).
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] At the other end, the spacecraft must decelerate for the gravity of Mars to capture it.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This capture burn should optimally be done at low altitude to also make best use of the Oberth effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Therefore, relatively small amounts of thrust at either end of the trip are needed to arrange the transfer compared to the free space situation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] However, with any Hohmann transfer, the alignment of the two planets in their orbits is crucial – the destination planet and the spacecraft must arrive at the same point in their respective orbits around the Sun at the same time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This requirement for alignment gives rise to the concept of launch windows.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The term lunar transfer orbit (LTO) is used for the Moon.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] It is possible to apply the formula given above to calculate the Δv in km/s needed to enter a Hohmann transfer orbit to arrive at various destinations from Earth (assuming circular orbits for the planets).
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In this table, the column labeled "Δv to enter Hohmann orbit from Earth's orbit" gives the change from Earth's velocity to the velocity needed to get on a Hohmann ellipse whose other end will be at the desired distance from the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The column labeled "LEO height" gives the velocity needed (in a non-rotating frame of reference centered on the earth) when 300 km above the Earth's surface.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This is obtained by adding to the specific kinetic energy the square of the escape velocity (10.93 km/s) from this height.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The column "LEO" is simply the previous speed minus the LEO orbital speed of 7.73 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Note that in most cases, Δ*v* from LEO is less than the Δ*v* to enter Hohmann orbit from Earth's orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] To get to the Sun, it is actually not necessary to use a Δ*v* of 24 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] One can use 8.8 km/s to go very far away from the Sun, then use a negligible Δ*v* to bring the angular momentum to zero, and then fall into the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This is also known as a bi-elliptic transfer, which is a sequence of two Hohmann transfers.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Also, the table does not give the values that would apply when using the Moon for a gravity assist.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] There are also possibilities of using one planet, like Venus which is the easiest to get to, to assist getting to other planets or the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The bi-elliptic transfer consists of two half-elliptic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] From the initial orbit, a first burn expends delta-v to boost the spacecraft into the first transfer orbit with an apoapsis at some point $r_{b}$ away from the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] At this point a second burn sends the spacecraft into the second elliptical orbit with periapsis at the radius of the final desired orbit, where a third burn is performed, injecting the spacecraft into the desired orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The idea of the bi-elliptical transfer trajectory was first published by Ary Sternfeld in 1934.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Low-thrust engines can perform an approximation of a Hohmann transfer orbit, by creating a gradual enlargement of the initial circular orbit through carefully timed engine firings.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This requires a change in velocity (delta-*v*) that is greater than the two-impulse transfer orbit and takes longer to complete.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Engines such as ion thrusters are more difficult to analyze with the delta-*v* model.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] These engines offer a very low thrust and at the same time, much higher delta-*v* budget, much higher specific impulse, lower mass of fuel and engine.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] A 2-burn Hohmann transfer maneuver would be impractical with such a low thrust; the maneuver mainly optimizes the use of fuel, but in this situation there is relatively plenty of it.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] If only low-thrust maneuvers are planned on a mission, then continuously firing a low-thrust, but very high-efficiency engine might generate a higher delta-*v* and at the same time use less propellant than a conventional chemical rocket engine.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Going from one circular orbit to another by gradually changing the radius simply requires the same delta-*v* as the difference between the two speeds.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Such maneuver requires more delta-*v* than a 2-burn Hohmann transfer maneuver, but does so with continuous low thrust rather than the short applications of high thrust.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The amount of propellant mass used measures the efficiency of the maneuver plus the hardware employed for it.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The total delta-*v* used measures the efficiency of the maneuver only.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For electric propulsion systems, which tend to be low-thrust, the high efficiency of the propulsive system usually compensates for the higher delta-V compared to the more efficient Hohmann maneuver.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Transfer orbits using electrical propulsion or low-thrust engines optimize the transfer time to reach the final orbit and not the delta-v as in the Hohmann transfer orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For geostationary orbit, the initial orbit is set to be supersynchronous and by thrusting continuously in the direction of the velocity at apogee, the transfer orbit transforms to a circular geosynchronous one.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This method however takes much longer to achieve due to the low thrust injected into the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In 1997, a set of orbits known as the Interplanetary Transport Network (ITN) was published, providing even lower propulsive delta-*v* (though much slower and longer) paths between different orbits than Hohmann transfer orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Interplanetary Transport Network is different in nature than Hohmann transfers because Hohmann transfers assume only one large body whereas the Interplanetary Transport Network does not.
[src:orbital-mechanics/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Interplanetary Transport Network is able to achieve the use of less propulsive delta-*v* by employing gravity assist from the planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In celestial mechanics, a **Kepler orbit** (or **Keplerian orbit**, named after the German astronomer Johannes Kepler) is the motion of one body relative to another, in the form of an ellipse, parabola, or hyperbola, which forms a two-dimensional orbital plane in three-dimensional space.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] A Kepler orbit can also tend toward a straight line.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] It considers only the point-like gravitational attraction of two bodies, neglecting perturbations due to gravitational interactions with other objects, atmospheric drag, solar radiation pressure, a non-spherical central body, and so on.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] It is thus said to be a solution of a special case of the two-body problem, known as the Kepler problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] As a theory in classical mechanics, it also does not take into account the effects of general relativity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Keplerian orbits can be parameterized into six orbital elements in various ways.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In most applications, there is a large central body, the center of mass of which is assumed to be the center of mass of the entire system.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The orbits of two objects of similar mass can be described as Kepler orbits around their common center of mass, their barycenter.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] From ancient times until the 16th and 17th centuries, the motions of the planets were believed to follow perfectly circular geocentric paths as taught by the ancient Greek philosophers Aristotle and Ptolemy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Variations in the motions of the planets were explained by smaller circular paths overlaid on the larger path (see epicycle).
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] As measurements of the planets became increasingly accurate, revisions to the theory were proposed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In 1543, Nicolaus Copernicus published a heliocentric model of the Solar System, although he still believed that the planets traveled in perfectly circular paths centered on the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In 1601, Johannes Kepler acquired the extensive, meticulous observations of the planets made by Tycho Brahe.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Kepler would spend the next five years trying to fit the observations of the planet Mars to various curves.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In 1609, Kepler published the first two of his three laws of planetary motion.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] More generally, the path of an object undergoing Keplerian motion may also follow a parabola or a hyperbola, which, along with ellipses, belong to a group of curves known as conic sections.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Where p is called the semi-latus rectum of the curve.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This form of the equation is particularly useful when dealing with parabolic trajectories, for which the semi-major axis is infinite.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Despite developing these laws from observations, Kepler was never able to develop a theory to explain these motions.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Isaac Newton produced the first such theory based around the concept of gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Albert Einstein's general relativity is the current description of gravitation in modern physics.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The two-body problem in general relativity has no closed-form solutions.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Between 1665 and 1666, Isaac Newton developed several concepts related to motion, gravitation and differential calculus.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] However, these concepts were not published until 1687 in the Principia, in which he outlined his laws of motion and his law of universal gravitation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Strictly speaking, this form of the equation only applies to an object of constant mass, which holds true based on the simplifying assumptions made below.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] From the laws of motion and the law of universal gravitation, Newton was able to derive Kepler's laws, which are specific to orbital motion in astronomy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Since Kepler's laws were well-supported by observation data, this consistency provided strong support of the validity of Newton's generalized theory, and unified celestial and ordinary mechanics.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] These laws of motion formed the basis of modern celestial mechanics until Albert Einstein introduced the concepts of special and general relativity in the early 20th century.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] For most applications, Keplerian motion approximates the motions of planets and satellites to relatively high degrees of accuracy and is used extensively in astronomy and astrodynamics.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] There are no external or internal forces acting upon the bodies other than their mutual gravitation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The shapes of large celestial bodies are close to spheres.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] By symmetry, the net gravitational force attracting a mass point towards a homogeneous sphere must be directed towards its centre.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The shell theorem (also proven by Isaac Newton) states that the magnitude of this force is the same as if all mass was concentrated in the middle of the sphere, even if the density of the sphere varies with depth (as it does for most celestial bodies).
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] From this immediately follows that the attraction between two homogeneous spheres is as if both had its mass concentrated to its center.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Smaller objects, like asteroids or spacecraft often have a shape strongly deviating from a sphere.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] But the gravitational forces produced by these irregularities are generally small compared to the gravity of the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The difference between an irregular shape and a perfect sphere also diminishes with distances, and most orbital distances are very large when compared with the diameter of a small orbiting body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Thus for some applications, shape irregularity can be neglected without significant impact on accuracy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This effect is quite noticeable for artificial Earth satellites, especially those in low orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Planets rotate at varying rates and thus may take a slightly oblate shape because of the centrifugal force.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] With such an oblate shape, the gravitational attraction will deviate somewhat from that of a homogeneous sphere.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] At larger distances the effect of this oblateness becomes negligible.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Planetary motions in the Solar System can be computed with sufficient precision if they are treated as point masses.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] and $\mathbf {\hat {r}}$ is the unit vector in that direction and r is the length of that vector.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] When compared to the central body, the mass of the orbiting body is insignificant.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This assumption is not necessary to solve the simplified two body problem, but it simplifies calculations, particularly with Earth-orbiting satellites and planets orbiting the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Even Jupiter's mass is less than the Sun's by a factor of 1047, which would constitute an error of 0.096% in the value of α.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Notable exceptions include the Earth-Moon system (mass ratio of 81.3), the Pluto-Charon system (mass ratio of 8.9) and binary star systems.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Under these assumptions the differential equation for the two body case can be completely solved mathematically and the resulting orbit which follows Kepler's laws of planetary motion is called a "Kepler orbit".
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The orbits of all planets are to high accuracy Kepler orbits around the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The small deviations are due to the much weaker gravitational attractions between the planets, and in the case of Mercury, due to general relativity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The orbits of the artificial satellites around the Earth are, with a fair approximation, Kepler orbits with small perturbations due to the gravitational attraction of the Sun, the Moon and the oblateness of the Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In high accuracy applications for which the equation of motion must be integrated numerically with all gravitational and non-gravitational forces (such as solar radiation pressure and atmospheric drag) being taken into account, the Kepler orbit concepts are of paramount importance and heavily used.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Any Keplerian trajectory can be defined by six parameters.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The motion of an object moving in three-dimensional space is characterized by a position vector and a velocity vector.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Each vector has three components, so the total number of values needed to define a trajectory through space is six.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] An orbit is generally defined by six elements (known as *Keplerian elements*) that can be computed from position and velocity, three of which have already been discussed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] These elements are convenient in that of the six, five are unchanging for an unperturbed orbit (a stark contrast to two constantly changing vectors).
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The future location of an object within its orbit can be predicted and its new position and velocity can be easily obtained from the orbital elements.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Because i , $\Omega$ and $\omega$ are simply angular measurements defining the orientation of the trajectory in the reference frame, they are not strictly necessary when discussing the motion of the object within the orbital plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] They have been mentioned here for completeness, but are not required for the proofs below.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Since the cross product of the position vector and its velocity stays constant, they must lie in the same plane, orthogonal to $\mathbf {H}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This implies the vector function is a plane curve.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Because the equation has symmetry around its origin, it is easier to solve in polar coordinates.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] However, equation (**1**) refers to linear acceleration $\left({\ddot {\mathbf {r} }}\right),$ as opposed to angular $\left({\ddot {\theta }}\right)$ or radial $\left({\ddot {r}}\right)$ acceleration.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Therefore, one must be cautious when transforming the equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] In order to solve this equation, all time derivatives must be eliminated.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Equations (**3**) and (**4**) can be used to eliminate the time derivatives of $\theta$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Instead of using the constant of integration $\theta _{0}$ explicitly one introduces the convention that the unit vectors ${\hat {x}},{\hat {y}}$ defining the coordinate system in the orbital plane are selected such that $\theta _{0}$ takes the value zero and *e* is positive.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This then means that $\theta$ is zero at the point where s is maximal and therefore $r={\tfrac {1}{s}}$ is minimal.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Notice that $(r,\theta )$ are effectively the polar coordinates of the vector function.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This is the equation in polar coordinates for a conic section with origin in a focal point.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The argument $\theta$ is called "true anomaly".
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Notice also that, since $\theta$ is the angle between the position vector $\mathbf {r}$ and the integration constant $\mathbf {c}$ , the vector $\mathbf {c}$ must be pointing in the direction of the **periapsis** of the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] where $\mathbf {H} =\mathbf {r} \times {\dot {\mathbf {r} }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {v}$ is the constant angular momentum vector of the orbit, and $\mathbf {v}$ is the velocity vector associated with the position vector $\mathbf {r}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] Obviously, the **eccentricity vector**, having the same direction as the integration constant $\mathbf {c}$ , also points to the direction of the **periapsis** of the orbit, and it has the magnitude of orbital eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This makes it very useful in orbit determination (OD) for the orbital elements of an orbit when a **state vector** [ $\mathbf {r} ,\mathbf {\dot {r}}$ ] or [ $\mathbf {r} ,\mathbf {v}$ ] is known.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] For $e=0$ this is a circle with radius *p*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The point on the horizontal line going out to the right from the focal point is the point with $\theta =0$ for which the distance to the focus takes the minimal value ${\tfrac {p}{1+e}},$ the pericentre.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The connection between the polar argument $\theta$ and time *t* is slightly different for elliptic and hyperbolic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] under the assumption that time $t=0$ is selected such that the integration constant is zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] To find what time, t, corresponds to a certain true anomaly $\theta$ it is necessary to compute the corresponding parameter *E* connected to time with relation (**27**) for an elliptic and with relation (**34**) for a hyperbolic orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] From the geometrical construction defining the eccentric anomaly it is clear that the vectors $(\cos E,\sin E)$ and $(\cos \theta ,\sin \theta )$ are on the same side of the *x*-axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] From this then follows that the vectors $\left(\cos {\tfrac {E}{2}},\sin {\tfrac {E}{2}}\right)$ and $\left(\cos {\tfrac {\theta }{2}},\sin {\tfrac {\theta }{2}}\right)$ are in the same quadrant.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] For the numerical computation of $\arg(x,y)$ the standard function ATAN2(y,x) (or in double precision DATAN2(y,x)) available in for example the programming language FORTRAN can be used.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This relation is convenient for passing between "true anomaly" and the parameter *E*, the latter being connected to time through relation (**34**).
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The equation of the center relates mean anomaly to true anomaly for elliptical orbits, for small numerical eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This is a parabola with focal length f and focus at the origin.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The parabola extends to minus infinity in x .
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] By Kepler's Second Law of equal areas in equal times this must be proportional to the time t since the periapsis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] By conservation of energy, the sum of the kinetic energy $KE$ and potential energy $PE$ must not depend upon $\theta$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This makes the total energy be zero, as expected.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This is Barker's equation and can be solved exactly for $\theta (t)$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] one gets a Kepler orbit that for true anomaly $\theta$ has the same r, $V_{r}$ and $V_{t}$ values as those defined by (**50**) and (**51**).
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] For any state vector $(\mathbf {r} ,\mathbf {v} )$ the Kepler orbit corresponding to this state can be computed with the algorithm defined above.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] First the parameters $p,e,\theta$ are determined from $r,V_{r},V_{t}$ and then the orthogonal unit vectors in the orbital plane ${\hat {x}},{\hat {y}}$ using the relations (**56**) and (**57**).
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The Kepler orbit computed in this way having the same "state vector" as the solution to the "equation of motion" (**59**) at time t is said to be "osculating" at this time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] is a small "perturbing force" due to for example a faint gravitational pull from other celestial bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] The parameters of the osculating Kepler orbit will then only slowly change and the osculating Kepler orbit is a good approximation to the real orbit for a considerable time period before and after the time of osculation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] This concept can also be useful for a rocket during powered flight as it then tells which Kepler orbit the rocket would continue in case the thrust is switched off.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] For a "close to circular" orbit the concept "eccentricity vector" defined as $\mathbf {e} =e{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ is useful.
[src:orbital-mechanics/kepler-orbit] i.e. $\mathbf {e}$ is a smooth differentiable function of the state vector $(\mathbf {r} ,\mathbf {v} )$ also if this state corresponds to a circular orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] A real orbit and its elements change over time due to gravitational perturbations by other objects and the effects of general relativity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] A Kepler orbit is an idealized, mathematical approximation of the orbit at a particular time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] When viewed from an inertial frame, two orbiting bodies trace out distinct trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Each of these trajectories has its focus at the common center of mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] When viewed from a non-inertial frame centered on one of the bodies, only the trajectory of the opposite body is apparent; Keplerian elements describe these non-inertial trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] An orbit has two sets of Keplerian elements depending on which body is used as the point of reference.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The reference body (usually the most massive) is called the *primary*, the other body is called the *secondary*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The primary does not necessarily possess more mass than the secondary, and even when the bodies are of equal mass, the orbital elements depend on the choice of the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Orbital elements can be obtained from orbital state vectors (position and velocity vectors of the orbiting object) by manual transformations or with computer software through a process known as orbit determination.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Non-closed orbits exist, although these are typically referred to as trajectories and not orbits, as they are not periodic.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The same elements used to describe closed orbits can also typically be used to represent open trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] A set of six orbital elements are needed to unambiguously define a Keplerian orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This is because the problem contains six degrees of freedom.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] These correspond to the six parameters defined in a set of orbital state vectors: three spatial dimensions which define position (*x*, *y*, *z* in a Cartesian coordinate system), and the velocity in each of these dimensions.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The orbiting object's trajectory is completely defined by the orbital state vectors, but this is often an inconvenient and opaque way to represent the orbit, which is why orbital elements are commonly used instead.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Such a set of 6 elements, however, only describes the starting position of the orbiting object and the shape of its trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] If one wants to use a set of orbital elements to solve Kepler's problem, two additional parameters must be included.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This is to say, in order to solve for the position and velocity of the orbiting object at an arbitrary future time, an extended set of eight orbital elements will be required.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] When describing an orbit with orbital elements, typically two are needed to describe the size and shape of the trajectory, three are needed to describe the rotation of the orbit, and one is needed to describe the starting position along the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] These can then be extended to include an element describing the speed of motion, and an element describing the time that the starting position occurs if position as a function of time needs to be solved.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Two parameters are required to describe the size and the shape of an orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Generally any two of these values can be used to calculate any other (as described below), so the choice of which to use is one of preference and the particular use case.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] For perfectly circular orbits, there is no distinct apoapsis or periapsis, as all points of the orbit have the same distance from the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Additionally, it is common to see the affix for "apoapsis" and "periapsis" changed depending on the central body (e.g.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] "apogee" and "perigee" for orbits of the Earth, and "aphelion" and "perihelion" for orbits of the Sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Other parameters can also be used to describe the size and shape of an orbit, such as the linear eccentricity, flattening, and focal parameter, but the use of these is limited.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This section contains the common relations between these orbital elements, but more relations can be derived through manipulations of one or more of these equations.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The variable names used here are consistent with the ones described above.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The semi-major axis can be found using the fact that the lines that connects the apoapsis to the center of the conic and from the center to the periapsis both combined span the length of the conic, and thus the major axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Three parameters are required to describe the orientation of the plane of the orbit and the orientation of the orbit within that plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] These three elements together can be described as Euler angles defining the orientation of the orbit relative to the reference coordinate system.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Although these three are the most common, other elements do exist and are useful to describe other properties of the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] One parameter is required to describe the speed of motion of the orbiting object around the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] However, this can be omitted if only a description of the shape of the orbit is required.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Various quantities that do not directly describe a speed can be used to satisfy this condition, and it is possible to convert from one to any other (formula below).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This section contains the common relations between the set of orbital elements described above, but more relations can be derived through manipulations of one or more of these equations.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Mean motion can be calculated using the standard gravitational parameter and the semi-major axis of the orbit. $n~={\sqrt {\;\!{\frac {\mu }{\ |a|^{3}}}~}}~.$ This equation returns the mean motion in radians and will need to be converted if n is desired to be in a different unit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Because the semi-major axis is related to the mean motion and standard gravitational parameter, it can be calculated without being specified.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This is especially useful if μ is assumed to be known, as then n can be used to calculate a, and likewise for specifying a.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This can allow one less element to specified.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Two elements are needed to describe the position of the body around its orbit and the time at which this occurs.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] If this time is defined to be at a point where the specific position variable is a designated constant (usually zero), then it does not need to be specified.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] These elements are also used to describe the position of an object in its orbit in a more general context and are not limited to describing the state at an epoch time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] These formulae also hold true for conversions between these elements in general.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Eccentric anomaly can be found with the mean anomaly and eccentricity using Kepler's equation $E\ =\ M+e\sin E$ through various means, such as iterative calculations or numerical solutions (for some values of e).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Typically a starting guess of either $\ M\ ,$ $\ M-e\ ,$ $\ M+e\ ,$ or $\ M+e\sin M\$ are used.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This iteration can be repeated until a desired level of tolerance is reached.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] While in theory, any set of elements that meets the requirements above can be used to describe an orbit, in practice, certain sets are much more common than others.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The most common elements used to describe the size and shape of the orbit are the semi-major axis (a) and the eccentricity (e).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Sometimes the semi-parameter (p) is used instead of the semi-major axis, as the semi-major axis experiences a singularity for parabolic trajectories, and thus cannot be used for this case.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] It is common to specify the period (P) or mean motion (n) instead of the semi-major axis in Keplerian element sets, as each can be computed from the other provided the standard gravitational parameter ( $\mu$ ) is known for the central body though the relations above.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] For the epoch, the epoch time (t) along with the mean anomaly (*M*0), mean longitude (*L*0), true anomaly ( $\nu _{0}$ ) or (more rarely) the eccentric anomaly (*E*0) are often used.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The time of periapsis passage (*T*0) is also sometimes used for this purpose, since using it eliminates the need to specify position at the epoch.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] It is also quite common to see either the mean anomaly or the mean longitude expressed directly, without either *M*0 or *L*0 as intermediary steps, as a linear function of time: $M(t)=M_{0}+n(t-t_{0}).$ This method of expression consolidates the mean motion as the slope of this linear equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The choice of elements can differ depending on the type of astronomical body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The eccentricity (*e*) and either the semi-major axis (*a*) or the distance of periapsis (*q*) are used to specify the shape and size of an orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The longitude of the ascending node (Ω) the inclination (*i*) and the argument of periapsis (*ω*) or the longitude of periapsis (*ϖ*) specify the orientation of the orbit in its plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Either the Mean longitude at epoch (*L*0) the mean anomaly at epoch (*M*0) or the time of periapsis passage (*T*0) are used to specify a known point in the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The choices made depend whether the vernal equinox or the node are used as the primary reference.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Orbital elements can be encoded as text in a number of formats.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The most common of them is the NASA / NORAD **"two-line elements"** (TLE) format, originally designed for use with 80-column punched cards, but still in use because it is the most common format, and 80-character ASCII records can be handled efficiently by modern databases.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The two-line element format lists the eccentricity (e), inclination (i), longitude of the ascending node (Ω), argument of periapsis (ω), mean motion (n), epoch (*t*0), and mean anomaly at epoch (*M*0).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Since the format is primarily meant for orbits of the Earth, the standard gravitational parameter (μ), can be assumed and used to calculate the semi-major axis with the mean motion via the relations above.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Depending on the application and object orbit, the data derived from TLEs older than 30 days can become unreliable.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Orbital positions can be calculated from TLEs through simplified perturbations models (SGP4 / SDP4 / SGP8 / SDP8).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The Delaunay orbital elements were introduced by Charles-Eugène Delaunay during his study of the motion of the Moon.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Commonly called *Delaunay variables*, they are a set of canonical variables, which are action-angle coordinates.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] along with their respective conjugate momenta L, G, and H.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The momenta L, G, and H are the *action* variables and are more elaborate combinations of the Keplerian elements a, e, and i.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Delaunay variables are used to simplify perturbative calculations in celestial mechanics, for example, while investigating the Kozai–Lidov oscillations in hierarchical triple systems.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The advantage of the Delaunay variables is that they remain well defined and non-singular (except for h, which can be tolerated) even for circular and equatorial orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Unperturbed, two-body, Newtonian orbits are always conic sections, so the Keplerian elements define an unchanging ellipse, parabola, or hyperbola.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Real orbits have perturbations, so a given set of Keplerian elements accurately describes an orbit only at the epoch.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Evolution of the orbital elements takes place due to the gravitational pull of bodies other than the primary, the non-sphericity of the primary, atmospheric drag, relativistic effects, radiation pressure, electromagnetic forces, and so on.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Keplerian elements can be used to produce useful predictions of a location of a moving body on its orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Perturbed trajectories can be modeled as a sequence of Keplerian orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Usually, these instantaneous orbits are chosen to be osculating.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] This means that they osculate ("kiss" or touch) the real trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] The evolution of the orbital elements defining instantaneous orbits is described by the so-called planetary equations, differential equations which come in different forms developed by Lagrange, Gauss, Delaunay, Poincaré, or Hill.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-elements] Be mindful that in some situations planetary equations in at least two standard types of orbital elements (Lagrange-type or Delaunay-type), when perturbed, produce elements that turn out to be non-osculating.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Celestial mechanics treats more broadly the orbit dynamics of systems under the influence of gravity, including both spacecraft and natural astronomical bodies such as star systems, planets, moons, and comets.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Orbital mechanics focuses on spacecraft trajectories, including orbital maneuvers, orbital plane changes, and interplanetary transfers, and is used by mission planners to predict the results of propulsive maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] General relativity is a more exact theory than Newton's laws for calculating orbits, and it is sometimes necessary to use it for greater accuracy or in high-gravity situations (e.g. orbits near the Sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Until the rise of space travel in the twentieth century, there was little distinction between orbital and celestial mechanics.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] At the time of Sputnik, the field was termed **space dynamics**.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The fundamental techniques, such as those used to solve the Keplerian problem (determining position as a function of time), are therefore the same in both fields.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Furthermore, the history of the fields is almost entirely shared.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Johannes Kepler was the first to successfully model planetary orbits to a high degree of accuracy, publishing his laws in 1609.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Isaac Newton published more general laws of celestial motion in the first edition of *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (1687), which gave a method for finding the orbit of a body following a parabolic path from three observations.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This was used by Edmund Halley to establish the orbits of various comets, including that which bears his name.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Newton's method of successive approximation was formalised into an analytic method by Leonhard Euler in 1744, whose work was in turn generalised to elliptical and hyperbolic orbits by Johann Lambert in 1761–1777.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Another milestone in orbit determination was Carl Friedrich Gauss's assistance in the "recovery" of the dwarf planet Ceres in 1801.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Gauss's method was able to use just three observations (in the form of pairs of right ascension and declination), to find the six orbital elements that completely describe an orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The theory of orbit determination has subsequently been developed to the point where today it is applied in GPS receivers as well as the tracking and cataloguing of newly observed minor planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Modern orbit determination and prediction are used to operate all types of satellites and space probes, as it is necessary to know their future positions to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Astrodynamics was developed by astronomer Samuel Herrick beginning in the 1930s.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] He consulted the rocket scientist Robert Goddard and was encouraged to continue his work on space navigation techniques, as Goddard believed they would be needed in the future.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Numerical techniques of astrodynamics were coupled with new powerful computers in the 1960s, and humans were ready to travel to the Moon and return.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The following rules of thumb are useful for situations approximated by classical mechanics under the standard assumptions of astrodynamics outlined below.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The specific example discussed is of a satellite orbiting a planet, but the rules of thumb could also apply to other situations, such as orbits of small bodies around a star such as the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The consequences of the rules of orbital mechanics are sometimes counter-intuitive.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For example, if two spacecraft are in the same circular orbit and wish to dock, the trailing craft cannot simply fire its engines to accelerate towards the leading craft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This will change the shape of its orbit, causing it to gain altitude and slow down relative to the leading craft, thus moving away from the target.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The space rendezvous before docking normally takes multiple precisely calculated engine firings in multiple orbital periods, requiring hours or even days to complete.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] To the extent that the standard assumptions of astrodynamics do not hold, actual trajectories will vary from those calculated.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For example, simple atmospheric drag is another complicating factor for objects in low Earth orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] These rules of thumb are decidedly inaccurate when describing two or more bodies of similar mass, such as a binary star system (see n-body problem).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Celestial mechanics uses more general rules applicable to a wider variety of situations.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's laws of planetary motion, which can be mathematically derived from Newton's laws, hold strictly only in describing the motion of two gravitating bodies in the absence of non-gravitational forces; they also describe parabolic and hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] In the close proximity of large objects like stars the differences between classical mechanics and general relativity also become important.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The fundamental laws of astrodynamics are Newton's law of universal gravitation and Newton's laws of motion, while the fundamental mathematical tool is differential calculus.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] In a Newtonian framework, the laws governing orbits and trajectories are in principle time-symmetric.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Standard assumptions in astrodynamics include non-interference from outside bodies, negligible mass for one of the bodies, and negligible other forces (such as from the solar wind, atmospheric drag, etc.).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] More accurate calculations can be made without these simplifying assumptions, but they are more complicated.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The increased accuracy often does not make enough of a difference in the calculation to be worthwhile.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's laws of planetary motion may be derived from Newton's laws, when it is assumed that the orbiting body is subject only to the gravitational force of the central attractor.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] When an engine thrust or propulsive force is present, Newton's laws still apply, but Kepler's laws are invalidated.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] When the thrust stops, the resulting orbit will be different but will once again be described by Kepler's laws which have been set out above.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] A line joining a planet and the Sun sweeps out equal areas during equal intervals of time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The squares of the orbital periods of planets are directly proportional to the cubes of the semi-major axis of the orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The formula for an escape velocity is derived as follows.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The specific energy (energy per unit mass) of any space vehicle is composed of two components, the specific potential energy and the specific kinetic energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The specific potential energy associated with a planet of mass *M* is given by $\epsilon _{p}=-{\frac {GM}{r}},$ where *G* is the gravitational constant and *r* is the distance between the two bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The specific kinetic energy of an object is given by $\epsilon _{k}={\frac {v^{2}}{2}},$ where *v* is its velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Since energy is conserved, $\epsilon$ cannot depend on the distance, r , from the center of the central body to the space vehicle in question, i.e.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] *v* must vary with *r* to keep the specific orbital energy constant.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The escape velocity from the Earth's surface is about 11 km/s, but that is insufficient to send the body an infinite distance because of the gravitational pull of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The parameter $\theta$ is known as the true anomaly, p is the semi-latus rectum, while e is the orbital eccentricity, all obtainable from the various forms of the six independent orbital elements.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] All bounded orbits where the gravity of a central body dominates are elliptical in nature.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] A special case of this is the circular orbit, which is an ellipse of zero eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Centrifugal acceleration matches the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] To properly use this formula, the units must be consistent; for example, M must be in kilograms, and r must be in meters, then the answer will be in meters per second.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The quantity $GM$ is often termed the standard gravitational parameter, which has a different value for every planet or moon in the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] To escape from gravity, the kinetic energy must at least match the negative potential energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] If $0<e<1$ , then the denominator of the equation of free orbits varies with the true anomaly $\theta$ , but remains positive, never becoming zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The maximum value r is reached when $\theta =180^{\circ }$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Let $2a$ be the distance measured along the apse line from periapsis P to apoapsis A : $2a=r_{p}+r_{a}.$ Substituting the equations above, we get $a={\frac {p}{1-e^{2}}},$ where a is the semimajor axis of the ellipse.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Under standard assumptions the orbital period ( T ) of a body traveling along an elliptic orbit can be computed as $T=2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {a^{3}}{\mu }}},$ where $\mu$ is the standard gravitational parameter, and a is the length of the semi-major axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] As the true anomaly θ approaches 180°, the denominator approaches zero, so that *r* tends towards infinity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Hence, the energy of the trajectory for which *e* = 1 is zero, and is given by $\epsilon ={\frac {v^{2}}{2}}-{\frac {\mu }{r}}=0,$ where v is the speed of the orbiting body.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] If $e>1$ , the orbit formula $r={\frac {h^{2}}{\mu }}{\frac {1}{1+e\cos \theta }}$ describes the geometry of the hyperbolic orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The system consists of two symmetric curves.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The orbiting body occupies one of them; the other one is its empty mathematical image.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Clearly, the denominator of the equation above goes to zero when $\cos \theta =-1/e$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] We denote this value of true anomaly $\theta _{\infty }=\cos ^{-1}\left(-{\frac {1}{e}}\right),$ since the radial distance approaches infinity as the true anomaly approaches $\theta _{\infty }$ , known as the *true anomaly of the asymptote*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Observe that $\theta _{\infty }$ lies between 90° and 180°.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] One approach to calculating orbits (mainly used historically) is to use Kepler's equation: $M=E-\epsilon \sin E,$ where *M* is the mean anomaly, *E* is the eccentric anomaly, and $\epsilon$ is the eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Compute the time of flight t from the eccentric anomaly E .
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Finding the eccentric anomaly at a given time (the inverse problem) is more difficult.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's equation is transcendental in E , meaning that it cannot be solved for E algebraically.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's equation can be solved for E analytically by inversion.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Alternatively, Kepler's equation can be solved numerically.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] First, one must guess a value of E and solve for time of flight; then adjust E as necessary to bring the computed time of flight closer to the desired value until the required precision is achieved.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Usually, Newton's method is used to achieve relatively fast convergence.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The main difficulty with this approach is that it can take prohibitively long to converge for the extreme elliptical orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For near-parabolic orbits, eccentricity $\epsilon$ is nearly 1, and substituting $e=1$ into the formula for mean anomaly, $E-\sin E$ , we find ourselves subtracting two nearly equal values, and accuracy suffers.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For near-circular orbits, it is hard to find the periapsis in the first place (and truly circular orbits have no periapsis at all).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Furthermore, the equation was derived on the assumption of an elliptical orbit, and so it does not hold for parabolic or hyperbolic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] These difficulties are what led to the development of the universal variable formulation, described below.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For simple procedures, such as computing the delta-v for coplanar transfer ellipses, traditional approaches are fairly effective.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Others, such as time-of-flight are far more complicated, especially for near-circular and hyperbolic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The Hohmann transfer orbit alone is a poor approximation for interplanetary trajectories because it neglects the planets' own gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Planetary gravity dominates the behavior of the spacecraft in the vicinity of a planet and in most cases Hohmann severely overestimates delta-v, and produces highly inaccurate prescriptions for burn timings.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] A relatively simple way to get a first-order approximation of delta-v is based on the "patched conic approximation" technique.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] One must choose the one dominant gravitating body in each region of space through which the trajectory will pass, and to model only that body's effects in that region.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For instance, on a trajectory from the Earth to Mars, one would begin by considering only the Earth's gravity until the trajectory reaches a distance where the Earth's gravity no longer dominates that of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The spacecraft would be given escape velocity to send it on its way to interplanetary space.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Next, one would consider only the Sun's gravity until the trajectory reaches the neighborhood of Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] During this stage, the transfer orbit model is appropriate.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Finally, only Mars's gravity is considered during the final portion of the trajectory where Mars's gravity dominates the spacecraft's behavior.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The spacecraft would approach Mars on a hyperbolic orbit, and a final retrograde burn would slow the spacecraft enough to be captured by Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Friedrich Zander was one of the first to apply the patched-conics approach for astrodynamics purposes, when proposing the use of intermediary bodies' gravity for interplanetary travels, in what is known today as a gravity assist.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This simplification is sufficient to compute rough estimates of fuel requirements, and rough time-of-flight estimates, but it is not generally accurate enough to guide a spacecraft to its destination.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For that, numerical methods are required.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] To address the computational shortcomings of traditional approaches for solving the 2-body problem, the universal variable formulation was developed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] It works equally well for the circular, elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic cases, the differential equations converging well when integrated for any orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] It also generalizes well to problems incorporating perturbation theory.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The universal variable formulation works well with the variation of parameters technique, except now, instead of the six Keplerian orbital elements, we use a different set of orbital elements: namely, the satellite's initial position and velocity vectors $x_{0}$ and $v_{0}$ at a given epoch $t=0$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] In a two-body simulation, these elements are sufficient to compute the satellite's position and velocity at any time in the future, using the universal variable formulation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Conversely, at any moment in the satellite's orbit, we can measure its position and velocity, and then use the universal variable approach to determine what its initial position and velocity *would have been* at the epoch.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] In perfect two-body motion, these orbital elements would be invariant (just like the Keplerian elements would be).
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] However, perturbations cause the orbital elements to change over time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Hence, the position element is written as $x_{0}(t)$ and the velocity element as $v_{0}(t)$ , indicating that they vary with time.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The technique to compute the effect of perturbations becomes one of finding expressions, either exact or approximate, for the functions $x_{0}(t)$ and $v_{0}(t)$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The following are some effects which make real orbits differ from the simple models based on a spherical Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Most of them can be handled on short timescales (perhaps less than a few thousand orbits) by perturbation theory because they are small relative to the corresponding two-body effects.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Over very long timescales (perhaps millions of orbits), even small perturbations can dominate, and the behavior can become chaotic.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] On the other hand, the various perturbations can be orchestrated by clever astrodynamicists to assist with orbit maintenance tasks, such as station-keeping, ground track maintenance or adjustment, or phasing of perigee to cover selected targets at low altitude.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] In spaceflight, an **orbital maneuver** is the use of propulsion systems to change the orbit of a spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For spacecraft far from Earth—for example those in orbits around the Sun—an orbital maneuver is called a *deep-space maneuver (DSM)*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Transfer orbits are usually elliptical orbits that allow spacecraft to move from one (usually substantially circular) orbit to another.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Usually, they require a burn at the start, a burn at the end, and sometimes one or more burns in the middle.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] For the case of orbital transfer between non-coplanar orbits, the change-of-plane thrust must be made at the point where the orbital planes intersect (the "node").
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] As the objective is to change the direction of the velocity vector by an angle equal to the angle between the planes, almost all of this thrust should be made when the spacecraft is at the node near the apoapse, when the magnitude of the velocity vector is at its lowest.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] However, a small fraction of the orbital inclination change can be made at the node near the periapse, by slightly angling the transfer orbit injection thrust in the direction of the desired inclination change.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] In a gravity assist, a spacecraft swings by a planet and leaves in a different direction, at a different speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This is useful to speed or slow a spacecraft instead of carrying more fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This maneuver can be approximated by an elastic collision at large distances, though the flyby does not involve any physical contact.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Due to Newton's third law (equal and opposite reaction), any momentum gained by a spacecraft must be lost by the planet, or vice versa.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] However, because the planet is much, much more massive than the spacecraft, the effect on the planet's orbit is negligible.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] The Oberth effect can be employed, particularly during a gravity assist operation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This effect is that use of a propulsion system works better at high speeds, and hence course changes are best done when close to a gravitating body; this can multiply the effective delta-v.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Orbital routes can be identified using nonlinear gravitational interactions between planets and moons in the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] These trajectories are part of the Interplanetary Transport Network and follow chaotic orbital paths that require minimal fuel beyond reaching a Lagrange point, with periodic course corrections.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Orbits can be plotted from high Earth orbit to Mars via an Earth trojan points.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] Limitations include long transit times, often taking several years, and infrequent launch windows.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] They have, however, been employed on projects such as Genesis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/orbital-mechanics] This spacecraft visited the Earth-Sun L1 point and returned using very little propellant.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The equation is named after—and usually credited to—Konstantin Tsiolkovsky, who derived and published the formula in 1903, though William Moore had outlined it as early as 1810 and elaborated further in a book published in 1813.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Robert Goddard and Hermann Oberth also obtained the same result in 1912 and 1920, respectively.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] All four of them reasoned and derived the same model independently.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The necessary wet mass grows exponentially with the desired delta-v.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The equation is named after Russian scientist Konstantin Tsiolkovsky who independently derived it and published it in his 1903 work.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The equation had been derived earlier by the British mathematician William Moore in 1810, and later published in a separate book in 1813.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] American Robert Goddard independently developed the equation in 1912 when he began his research to improve rocket engines for possible space flight.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] German engineer Hermann Oberth independently derived the equation about 1920 as he studied the feasibility of space travel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] While the derivation of the rocket equation is a straightforward calculus exercise, Tsiolkovsky is honored as being the first to apply it to the question of whether rockets could achieve speeds necessary for space travel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In the following derivation, "the rocket" is taken to mean "the rocket and all of its unexpended propellant".
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] If $v_{\text{e}}$ is NOT constant, we might not have rocket equations that are as simple as the above forms.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Many rocket dynamics researches were based on the Tsiolkovsky's constant $v_{\text{e}}$ hypothesis.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The value $m_{0}-m_{f}$ is the total working mass of propellant expended.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] $\Delta V$ (delta-v) is the integration over time of the magnitude of the acceleration produced by using the rocket engine (what would be the actual acceleration if external forces were absent).
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In free space, for the case of acceleration in the direction of the velocity, this is the increase of the speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In the case of an acceleration in opposite direction (deceleration) it is the decrease of the speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Of course gravity and drag also accelerate the vehicle, and they can add or subtract to the change in velocity experienced by the vehicle.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Hence delta-v may not always be the actual change in speed or velocity of the vehicle.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The equation can also be derived from the basic integral of acceleration in the form of force (thrust) over mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Imagine a rocket at rest in space with no forces exerted on it (Newton's first law of motion).
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] From the moment its engine is started (clock set to 0) the rocket expels gas mass at a *constant mass flow rate R* (kg/s) and at *exhaust velocity relative to the rocket ve* (m/s).
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] This creates a constant force *F* propelling the rocket that is equal to *R* × *ve*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The rocket is subject to a constant force, but its total mass is decreasing steadily because it is expelling gas.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Now, the mass of fuel the rocket initially has on board is equal to *m*0 – *mf*.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] For the constant mass flow rate *R* it will therefore take a time *T* = (*m*0 – *mf*)/*R* to burn all this fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Let $\phi$ be the initial fuel mass fraction on board and $m_{0}$ the initial fueled-up mass of the rocket.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Divide the total mass of fuel $\phi m_{0}$ into N discrete pellets each of mass $m_{p}=\phi m_{0}/N$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The remaining mass of the rocket after ejecting j pellets is then $m=m_{0}(1-j\phi /N)$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Delta-*v* (literally "change in velocity"), symbolised as **Δ*v*** and pronounced *delta-vee*, as used in spacecraft flight dynamics, is a measure of the impulse that is needed to perform a maneuver such as launching from, or landing on a planet or moon, or an in-space orbital maneuver.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] It is a scalar that has the units of speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] As used in this context, it is *not* the same as the physical change in velocity of the vehicle.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Delta-*v* is produced by reaction engines, such as rocket engines, is proportional to the thrust per unit mass and burn time, and is used to determine the mass of propellant required for the given manoeuvre through the rocket equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] For multiple manoeuvres, delta-*v* sums linearly.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] For interplanetary missions delta-*v* is often plotted on a porkchop plot which displays the required mission delta-*v* as a function of launch date.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In aerospace engineering, the propellant mass fraction is the portion of a vehicle's mass which does not reach the destination and is instead burned as propellant, usually used as a measure of the vehicle's performance.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In other words, the propellant mass fraction is the ratio between the propellant mass and the initial mass of the vehicle.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In a spacecraft, the destination is usually an orbit, while for aircraft it is their landing location.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] A higher mass fraction represents less weight in a design.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Another related measure is the payload fraction, which is the fraction of initial weight that is payload.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] While the original wording of the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation does not directly use the mass fraction, the mass fraction can be derived from the used ratio of initial to final mass, or ${\frac {m_{0}}{m_{f}}}={\frac {m_{f}+m_{p}}{m_{f}}}={\frac {m_{p}}{m_{f}}}+1$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The rocket equation captures the essentials of rocket flight physics in a single short equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] It also holds true for rocket-like reaction vehicles whenever the effective exhaust velocity is constant, and can be summed or integrated when the effective exhaust velocity varies.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The rocket equation only accounts for the reaction force from the rocket engine; it does not include other forces that may act on a rocket, such as aerodynamic or gravitational forces.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] As such, when using it to calculate the propellant requirement for launch from (or powered descent to) a planet with an atmosphere, the effects of these forces must be included in the delta-V requirement (see Examples below).
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] In what has been called "the tyranny of the rocket equation", there is a limit to the amount of payload that the rocket can carry, as higher amounts of propellant increment the overall weight, and thus also increase the fuel consumption.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The equation does not apply to non-rocket systems such as aerobraking, gun launches, space elevators, launch loops, tether propulsion or light sails.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] The rocket equation can be applied to orbital maneuvers in order to determine how much propellant is needed to change to a particular new orbit, or to find the new orbit as the result of a particular propellant burn.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] When applying to orbital maneuvers, one assumes an impulsive maneuver, in which the propellant is discharged and delta-v applied instantaneously.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] This assumption is relatively accurate for short-duration burns such as for mid-course corrections and orbital insertion maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] As the burn duration increases, the result is less accurate due to the effect of gravity on the vehicle over the duration of the maneuver.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] For low-thrust, long duration propulsion, such as electric propulsion, more complicated analysis based on the propagation of the spacecraft's state vector and the integration of thrust are used to predict orbital motion.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] Assume an exhaust velocity of 4,500 meters per second (15,000 ft/s) and a $\Delta v$ of 9,700 meters per second (32,000 ft/s) (Earth to LEO, including $\Delta v$ to overcome gravity and aerodynamic drag).
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] For each stage the specific impulse may be different.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] and the payload is 10% × 10% × 10% = 0.1% of the initial mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] A comparable SSTO rocket, also with a 0.1% payload, could have a mass of 11.1% for fuel tanks and engines, and 88.8% for fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics/tsiolkovsky-rocket-equation] If the motor of a new stage is ignited before the previous stage has been discarded and the simultaneously working motors have a different specific impulse (as is often the case with solid rocket boosters and a liquid-fuel stage), the situation is more complicated.
